// @test: parse-fail
// @tier: 0
// @level: L0
// @tags: parser, recovery, rust-macro, diagnostics, regression
// @expected-error: E0E2
// @expected-error-count: 3
//
// Regression for Issue #5 (root fix in
// crates/verum_fast_parser/src/expr.rs::parse_macro_call +
// crates/verum_fast_parser/src/decl.rs::parse_module).
//
// Two distinct bugs combined to inflate the diagnostic count on Rust-
// style macro syntax:
//
//   (a) `parse_macro_call` returned the "use `assert(...)` instead"
//       diagnostic without consuming the offending `ident!(...)` tokens,
//       so the outer statement loop retried at the same offset and
//       re-emitted the diagnostic on the next recovery pass.
//
//   (b) `parse_module` returned `Err(self.errors.first().clone())` when
//       the accumulated error list was non-empty; the caller in lib.rs
//       then pushed that clone back onto `parser.errors`, duplicating
//       the first diagnostic across the final list.
//
// With both fixes, the three `assert!` lines below produce exactly
// three distinct diagnostics — one per actual syntax mistake — and the
// parser stays synchronised on subsequent statements without cascading.

fn main() {
    assert!(1 == 1);
    assert!(2 == 2);
    assert!(3 == 3);
}
